<p class="text-align-center"><em>Planet Fitness has incorporated safety and cleanliness into its brand messaging, even trademarking the term &#8220;Cardio Distancing.&#8221;</em></p>
<h3><span lang="EN">Try nostalgia marketing</span></h3>
<p><span lang="EN">Meanwhile, Chris Vaughn<span lang="EN">, <span lang="EN">CEO of<span lang="EN"> <a href="https://pacificconsolidated.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Pacific Consolidated Holdings</a><span lang="EN">, a holding company focused on <a href="/blog/ws/2020/03/12/cannabis-marketing">cannabis</a> and other vice industries, <span lang="EN">expects more nostalgia as consumers crave â€œthe simplicity of their youths.â€</span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p><span lang="EN">He added, â€œConsumers are more likely to develop brand loyalty for a company they feel <a href="/blog/ws/2021/05/03/emotional-marketing-copy">emotionally</a> connected to and nostalgia marketing harnesses the positive, optimistic associations between customerâ€™s good old days and <a href="/blog/ws/2015/05/07/marketing-funnel">funnels</a> them into a brand.â€</span></p>
<h3><span lang="EN">Use scarcity tactics sparingly </span></h3>
<p><span lang="EN">On the other side of the coin, Catie Fromknecht, digital marketing consultant at consumer behavior research firm <a href="https://www.clicksuasion.com/">Clicksuasion Labs</a><span lang="EN">, noted consumers are more likely to be susceptible to scarcity marketing tactics following a year of substantial lossesâ€”but this tactic should be used sparingly.Â </span></span></p>
<h2>3. Make your brandâ€™s stances clear</h2>
<p><span lang="EN">In addition, brand messaging should adjust to reflect positioning on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/12/21/how-brands-are-embracing-social-change">social responsibility</a>.</span></p>
<h3><span lang="EN">Align with new consumer ethics</span></h3>
<p><span lang="EN">Citing figures from consulting firm Accenture, Arthur Iinuma, <span lang="EN">president of app development firm<span lang="EN"> <a href="https://www.isbx.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ISBX</a><span lang="EN">, <span lang="EN">noted <span lang="EN">COVID-19 has prompted a shift in consumer consciousness as 45% have adopted more sustainable habits and plan to continue to embrace these choices.Â </span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p><span lang="EN">â€œBrands must align with the new consumer sentiment and consider how they can promote a more <a href="/blog/ws/2017/09/20/ethical-marketing">ethical</a> model of consumerism,â€ he added.</span></p>
<h3><span lang="EN">Focus on diversity and inclusion.</span></h3>
<p><span lang="EN">â€œMany consumers now expect brands to show support in the fight against discrimination and other social issues [or they will] fall victim to the financial and moral consequences,â€ said <span lang="EN">Eden Cheng, co-founder of invoice platform<span lang="EN"> <a href="https://weinvoice.com/">WeInvoice</a><span lang="EN">.â€œ</span></span></span></span></p>
<p><span lang="EN">This has led to us making major commitments in our content marketing strategies that help emphasize our support in the fight against racial discrimination, as well as active participation in lending a hand to the local community through various social causes.â€</span></p>
